	doi = {10.1016/j.jembe.2013.02.028},
	abstract = {Responses by organisms to topographic amelioration of the environment are often assumed to represent direct associations between organisms and topographic features of rocky shores. Responses can also be indirect. For example, differences in environmental variables associated with topographic features can alter growth of biofilms of epilithic microphytobenthos. Understanding how microphytobenthos responds to local variations in environmental conditions helps to explain spatial patchiness in some intertidal assemblages. Effects of rockpools on temperatures, rates of water-flow and amounts and types of microphytobenthos were quantified using artificial units of habitat (sandstone slabs providing rockpools, non-rockpools and bare rock). Rockpools were cooler and water-flow was less than in other habitats. Amounts of moisture and microphytobenthos were greater around rockpools than elsewhere. Microphytobenthos was most similar to assemblages of cyanobacteria but did not differ among habitats during warm months (November-March). During cool months (May-August), pigments associated with cyanobacteria were less abundant around rock pools than elsewhere. The converse was true for green algae, which were more abundant around rockpools. Thus, micro-habitats had some predictable influences (water flow). Other variables changed predictably, but not always in expected ways (temperature). Yet other variables were far less predictable and the influence of micro-habitats may also extend beyond the immediate vicinity of the micro-habitat (microphytobenthos). To understand the effects of different topographies on hydrodynamics and the responses by organisms, it is essential that measurements are made at appropriate scales and in relation to the different micro-habitats in which they occur. To improve explanations of observed patterns of distribution and behaviour in environments subject to climatic and anthropogenic change, greater understanding of the influences of micro-habitats is required. © 2013 Elsevier B.V.},
